---
import ContentLayout from '@/layouts/content-layout.astro'
---

<ContentLayout
	title="AI Knowledge Pipeline — Ilzam"
	description="RAG pipeline with hybrid search — pgvector + BM25 for accurate document retrieval. Built with Go and PostgreSQL for a San Francisco AI company."
>
	<a href="/work" class="text-sm text-muted-foreground hover:text-foreground">&larr; All work</a>

	<div class="mt-6 flex items-center justify-between">
		<span class="rounded-sm bg-muted px-2 py-0.5 text-xs font-medium uppercase">AI / RAG</span>
		<span class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">San Francisco, US / 2025</span>
	</div>

	<h1 class="mt-4 text-4xl font-light leading-tight tracking-tight md:text-5xl">
		AI Knowledge Pipeline
	</h1>
	<p class="mt-2 text-lg text-muted-foreground">
		RAG that actually retrieves the right thing.
	</p>

	<div class="mt-4 flex flex-wrap gap-1.5">
		{["Go", "PostgreSQL", "pgvector", "BM25", "Markdown AST"].map((tech) => (
			<span class="rounded-full border px-2.5 py-0.5 text-xs">{tech}</span>
		))}
	</div>

	<section class="mt-12">
		<h2 class="text-xl font-semibold">The Challenge</h2>
		<p class="mt-3 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			A San Francisco AI company needed a retrieval-augmented generation pipeline that could accurately retrieve relevant documents from a large knowledge base. Pure vector search wasn't cutting it — semantic similarity alone missed keyword-specific matches, and the retrieval quality was inconsistent.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="mt-10">
		<h2 class="text-xl font-semibold">The Approach</h2>
		<p class="mt-3 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			I designed a hybrid search system combining pgvector (vector similarity) with BM25 (keyword matching), using Reciprocal Rank Fusion to merge results. Documents were chunked using Markdown AST parsing — preserving heading hierarchy and semantic structure instead of naive character splitting.
		</p>
		<p class="mt-3 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			Everything runs on PostgreSQL. No external vector database. No separate search engine. One database, two search strategies, fused results.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="mt-10">
		<h2 class="text-xl font-semibold">Key Decisions</h2>
		<ul class="mt-3 space-y-3 text-muted-foreground">
			<li class="leading-relaxed">
				<span class="font-medium text-foreground">pgvector over Pinecone.</span>
				Keeping everything in PostgreSQL meant no extra infrastructure, no API latency, and simpler deployments. For this scale, pgvector performed well enough — and the operational simplicity was worth more than marginal speed gains.
			</li>
			<li class="leading-relaxed">
				<span class="font-medium text-foreground">Markdown AST chunking over naive splitting.</span>
				Splitting by character count destroys context. Parsing the Markdown AST lets you chunk by semantic sections — a heading and its content stay together, producing more meaningful embeddings.
			</li>
			<li class="leading-relaxed">
				<span class="font-medium text-foreground">Hybrid search over pure vector.</span>
				Vector search is great for semantic similarity but misses exact matches. BM25 catches those. Fusing both with RRF gives consistently better retrieval quality than either alone.
			</li>
		</ul>
	</section>

	<section class="mt-10">
		<h2 class="text-xl font-semibold">The Result</h2>
		<p class="mt-3 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			Measurably better retrieval quality compared to the previous vector-only approach. The pipeline runs in production, serving real users daily. The architecture is simple enough that the internal team can maintain and extend it without specialized infrastructure knowledge.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="mt-12 border-t pt-8">
		<h3 class="text-sm font-medium uppercase tracking-wider text-muted-foreground">Related Notes</h3>
		<ul class="mt-3 space-y-2">
			<li><a href="/notes/pgvector-vs-pinecone-rag" class="text-sm underline underline-offset-4 hover:text-foreground">pgvector vs Pinecone for RAG</a></li>
			<li><a href="/notes/rag-chunking-markdown-ast" class="text-sm underline underline-offset-4 hover:text-foreground">RAG Chunking with Markdown AST</a></li>
			<li><a href="/notes/bm25-vector-rrf-retrieval-quality" class="text-sm underline underline-offset-4 hover:text-foreground">BM25 + Vector + RRF Retrieval Quality</a></li>
		</ul>
	</section>

	<section class="mt-10 rounded-lg bg-muted/50 p-6 text-center">
		<p class="font-medium">Building a RAG pipeline?</p>
		<p class="mt-1 text-sm text-muted-foreground">
			I've shipped this in production. If you want a second opinion on your approach, book a technical call.
		</p>
		<a
			href="https://cal.com/ilzam/technical"
			target="_blank"
			rel="noopener noreferrer"
			class="mt-4 inline-block rounded-full bg-foreground px-5 py-2 text-sm font-medium text-background transition-opacity hover:opacity-90"
		>
			Book a Technical Call
		</a>
	</section>
</ContentLayout>
